<DOC><DOCNO> AP901108-0201 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-11-08-90 2210EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Venezuela-Curfew     11-08 0190</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Venezuela-Curfew,0202</SECOND><HEAD>Venezuela Sets Curfew for Minors to Combat Crime Wave</HEAD><DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   In an effort to thwart rising crime,President Carlos Andres Perez announced a nighttime curfew forminors.   Those under age 18 caught on the streets after 10 p.m. will betaken to ``special areas,'' where their parents will be summonedor, in the case of parentless youths, taken to centers forabandoned children, Perez said Thursday.   ``This is another measure to stop an extremely serious (crime)situation we're facing with minors,'' the president said in aweekly radio broadcast.   An Interior Ministry spokesman said the curfew, which would takeeffect immediately, will be enforced by regular police.   Perez recently set up a special 600-member military NationalGuard force to help patrol Caracas.   Teenagers under age 18 are blamed for as much as 75 percent ofVenezuela's violent crime.   Citizens have protested against lenient laws that shield teenagecriminals and turn them into pawns of adult gangs; the youths maynot be jailed, and are often freed within days.   The rate of theft, mugging and murder has steadiy climbed inthis nation of 20 million recent years, as the economy declined.</TEXT></DOC>